{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/7069.The_World_According_to_Garp", "title": "The World According to Garp", "titleComplete": "The World According to Garp", "description": "This is the life and times of T. S. Garp, the bastard son of Jenny Fields\u2014a feminist leader ahead of her times. This is the life and death of a famous mother and her almost-famous son; theirs is a world of sexual extremes\u2014even of sexual assassinations. It is a novel rich with \"lunacy and sorrow\"; yet the dark, violent events of the story do not undermine a comedy both ribald and robust. In more than thirty languages, in more than forty countries\u2014with more than ten million copies in print\u2014this novel provides almost cheerful, even hilarious evidence of its famous last line: \"In the world according to Garp, we are all terminal cases.\"", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1447234581i/7069.jpg", "genres": ["Classics", "Contemporary", "Novels", "Drama", "Literature", "Literary Fiction", "Adult Fiction", "Humor", "American", "Fiction"], "asin": "0345915593", "isbn": "0345915593", "isbn13": "9780345915597", "publisher": "Ballantine Books", "author": ["John Irving"], "publishDate": 922953600000, "characters": ["Helen Garp", "T.S. Garp", "Jenny Fields", "Roberta Muldoon"], "places": ["The United States of America", "Austria", "Vienna", "Boston, Massachusetts", "New England"], "ratingHistogram": [3654, 9366, 38274, 85429, 91170], "ratingsCount": 227893, "reviewsCount": 6741, "numPages": 610, "language": "English", "awards": [{"name": "National Book Award", "awardedAt": 315561600000, "category": "Fiction (Paperback)", "hasWon": null}, {"name": "National Book Critics Circle Award", "awardedAt": 252489600000, "category": "Fiction", "hasWon": null}, {"name": "National Book Award Finalist", "awardedAt": 284025600000, "category": "Fiction", "hasWon": null}]}
{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/10222.The_Far_Pavilions", "title": "The Far Pavilions", "titleComplete": "The Far Pavilions", "description": "A magnificent romantic/historical/adventure novel set in India at the time of mutiny. The Far Pavilions is a story of 19th Century India, when the thin patina of English rule held down dangerously turbulent undercurrents. It is a story about and English man - Ashton Pelham-Martyn - brought up as a Hindu and his passionate, but dangerous love for an Indian princess. It's a story of divided loyalties, of tender camaraderie, of greedy imperialism and of the clash between east and west. To the burning plains and snow-capped mountains of this great, humming continent, M.M. Kaye brings her quite exceptional gift of immediacy and meticulous historical accuracy, plus her insight into the human heart.", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1403391799i/10222.jpg", "genres": ["Classics", "Asia", "Historical Romance", "India", "Historical", "Historical Fiction", "19th Century", "Fiction", "Romance", "Adventure"], "asin": "B004Y6MW0M", "isbn": "031215125X", "isbn13": "9780312151256", "publisher": "St. Martin's Griffin", "author": ["M.M. Kaye"], "publishDate": 853315200000, "places": ["Pakistan", "Rajasthan", "India", "Mardan", "Khyber Pakhtunkhwa", "South Asia", "Afghanistan"], "ratingHistogram": [538, 1433, 6940, 14820, 20210], "ratingsCount": 43941, "reviewsCount": 1630, "numPages": 958, "language": "English"}
{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/18490.Frankenstein", "title": "Frankenstein", "titleComplete": "Frankenstein", "description": "\n  'Now that I had finished, the beauty of the dream vanished, and breathless horror and disgust filled my heart ...'\nObsessed with creating life itself, Victor Frankenstein plunders graveyards for the material to fashion a new being, which he shocks into life with electricity. But his botched creature, rejected by Frankenstein and denied human companionship, sets out to destroy his maker and all that he holds dear. Mary Shelley's chilling Gothic tale was conceived when she was only eighteen, living with her lover Percy Shelley near Byron's villa on Lake Geneva. It would become the world's most famous work of horror fiction, and remains a devastating exploration of the limits of human creativity.Based on the third edition of 1831, this volume contains all the revisions Mary Shelley made to her story, as well as her 1831 introduction and Percy Bysshe Shelley's preface to the first edition. This revised edition includes as appendices a select collation of the texts of 1818 and 1831 together with 'A Fragment' by Lord Byron and Dr John Polidori's 'The Vampyre: A Tale'.", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1665008650i/18490.jpg", "genres": ["Novels", "Science Fiction", "Fantasy", "School", "Read For School", "Literature", "19th Century", "Gothic", "Horror", "Fiction"], "asin": "0141439475", "isbn": "0141439475", "isbn13": "9780141439471", "publisher": "Penguin", "author": ["Mary Wollstonecraft Shelley"], "publishDate": 1041408000000, "characters": ["William Frankenstein", "Agatha", "Henry Clerval", "Elizabeth Lavenza", "Alphonse Frankenstein", "Caroline Beaufort Frankenstein", "The Monster (Frankenstein)", "De Lacey", "Safie", "Victor Frankenstein", "Justine Moritz", "Felix", "Ernest Frankenstein", "Robert Walton"], "places": ["Geneva", "Germany", "Ingolstadt", "Arctic